1
00:01:22,115 --> 00:01:23,605
Will?

2
00:01:23,783 --> 00:01:24,977
What is it, Pa?

3
00:01:25,151 --> 00:01:26,880
Come out here.

4
00:01:31,291 --> 00:01:34,727
Listen. Your ears
are better than mine.

5
00:01:34,894 --> 00:01:37,454
Somebody's coming.

6
00:01:38,498 --> 00:01:39,692
I don't hear nothing.

7
00:01:39,866 --> 00:01:42,460
Turn off that whatchama-call-it.

8
00:01:42,635 --> 00:01:46,230
-The radio.
-I know what you call it. Turn it off.

9
00:01:47,607 --> 00:01:51,065
First, I heard one of
them cars. Then it stopped.

10
00:01:51,244 --> 00:01:53,804
And now somebody's
coming down the hill.

11
00:01:53,980 --> 00:01:55,572
You hear?

12
00:01:56,382 --> 00:01:58,976
Y'all stay right here.
If I call, come a-running.

13
00:02:04,090 --> 00:02:07,253
Pa, that ain't no way to
welcome folks. Maybe it's kin.

14
00:02:07,427 --> 00:02:09,691
Kin don't come in no cars.

15
00:02:09,862 --> 00:02:13,025
See if you can wake
up that old hound dog.

16
00:02:14,434 --> 00:02:15,458
Hey, Blue?

17
00:02:15,635 --> 00:02:18,695
Come on, Blue. I got a
big old catfish head for you.

18
00:02:18,871 --> 00:02:21,066
Come on, Blue.

19
00:02:21,240 --> 00:02:24,209
Never seen such a crickety
dang pit in my whole life.

20
00:02:24,377 --> 00:02:26,345
Stuck up all over
here and everything.

21
00:02:30,683 --> 00:02:32,878
-Are you Will Stockdale?
-Howdy.

22
00:02:34,287 --> 00:02:36,619
Three dang times this
month, I've been out here--

23
00:02:36,789 --> 00:02:39,519
Don't you point your
finger in my boy's face.

24
00:02:39,692 --> 00:02:41,660
Are you threatening
me with a firearm?

25
00:02:41,828 --> 00:02:44,092
I'm a government
representative on business.

26
00:02:44,263 --> 00:02:47,528
Busting up here without
saying howdy or nothing.

27
00:02:47,700 --> 00:02:51,636
-What government?
-U.S. government. The draft board.

28
00:02:51,804 --> 00:02:54,500
This boy's been called for
the draft. He never reported.

29
00:02:54,674 --> 00:02:55,732
He's a draft dodger.

30
00:02:55,908 --> 00:03:00,436
Fold in that finger, sir. I'm
warning you, fold in that finger.

31
00:03:00,613 --> 00:03:03,275
He could go to jail for
that. He's in today's group.

32
00:03:03,449 --> 00:03:04,814
And this is your last chance.

33
00:03:04,984 --> 00:03:07,111
If you don't leave with
that group at 12 a.m...

34
00:03:07,286 --> 00:03:10,380
...you're gonna be in more
trouble than you ever did see.

35
00:03:10,556 --> 00:03:12,524
You already got one
offense against you.

36
00:03:12,692 --> 00:03:15,183
-Not answering my letters.
-I never got no letters.

37
00:03:15,361 --> 00:03:18,853
Don't tell me you can't read. You
could've got somebody to read them to you.

38
00:03:19,031 --> 00:03:21,465
-So that ain't no excuse.
-You mean to stand there...

39
00:03:21,634 --> 00:03:24,125
...and tell me to my
face my boy can't read?

40
00:03:24,303 --> 00:03:26,100
-Now, look--
-You think my boy...

41
00:03:26,272 --> 00:03:27,705
...who has gone to school...

42
00:03:27,874 --> 00:03:31,002
...and who has read more times
than you could shake a stick at...

43
00:03:31,177 --> 00:03:34,305
...couldn't read a puny little
old letter, if he wanted to?

44
00:03:34,480 --> 00:03:35,913
By dog, sir.

45
00:03:36,082 --> 00:03:37,606
I never got no letters.

46
00:03:38,050 --> 00:03:41,144
I don't think I can stand
to listen to any more of this.

47
00:03:41,487 --> 00:03:43,455
Get that book.

48
00:03:44,090 --> 00:03:47,218
No, sir, what you think
don't mean nothing to me...

49
00:03:47,393 --> 00:03:50,794
...but we are gonna settle this
here question right here and now...

50
00:03:50,963 --> 00:03:54,126
...and not have no
more foolishness about it.

51
00:03:54,500 --> 00:03:56,331
Read at him.

52
00:04:01,474 --> 00:04:05,069
"Once there was a
boy named Tony...

53
00:04:05,244 --> 00:04:07,576
...who wanted a pony.

54
00:04:07,747 --> 00:04:11,547
So he went to his mama and said:

55
00:04:11,717 --> 00:04:14,311
'May I have a pony? '

56
00:04:14,487 --> 00:04:17,183
And his Mama says:

57
00:04:18,458 --> 00:04:22,986
'No, Tony, you may
not have a pony.'"

58
00:04:23,529 --> 00:04:25,292
Go on.

59
00:04:28,968 --> 00:04:32,961
"So he went to
his papa and said:

60
00:04:33,139 --> 00:04:36,700
'Papa, may I have a pony? '

61
00:04:36,876 --> 00:04:38,901
And his papa says:

62
00:04:39,078 --> 00:04:43,412
'No, Tony, you may not have...

63
00:04:44,350 --> 00:04:46,341
...a pony.'"

64
00:04:47,019 --> 00:04:49,112
End of the book, he
gets the pony anyhow.

65
00:04:49,288 --> 00:04:52,985
Now that we have settled
if or not my boy can read--

66
00:04:53,159 --> 00:04:55,559
-Pa.
--you best be getting off my property...

67
00:04:55,728 --> 00:04:58,196
...and back in that car of
yours and out of range--

68
00:04:58,364 --> 00:05:00,832
-Pa, be Christian to him.
-Christian?

69
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:02,900
You know what the
Lord would've done...

70
00:05:03,069 --> 00:05:06,232
...if a man come all hot and
stomping onto his property...

71
00:05:06,405 --> 00:05:08,202
...without saying
howdy or nothing?

72
00:05:08,407 --> 00:05:11,604
Scaring his chickens and
saying folks can't read?

73
00:05:12,712 --> 00:05:15,943
Sir, would it be all right if
me and Pa speak private-like?

74
00:05:16,115 --> 00:05:19,607
-Okay, but make it short.
-Thank you, sir.

75
00:05:19,785 --> 00:05:21,446
Come on, Pa.

76
00:05:21,754 --> 00:05:24,917
And don't try any funny business.
Because I ain't alone here.

77
00:05:26,926 --> 00:05:29,121
Set yourself, Pa.

78
00:05:31,864 --> 00:05:33,525
Now, listen, Pa.

79
00:05:33,699 --> 00:05:36,827
I don't think this here
draft's such a bad idea.

80
00:05:37,003 --> 00:05:39,130
I mean, I'd kind of like to go.

81
00:05:39,305 --> 00:05:43,765
There's a whole lot of fellas there and
they all march along right, snappy like.

82
00:05:43,943 --> 00:05:45,877
You listen to me, boy.

83
00:05:46,045 --> 00:05:49,276
Going in the draft don't
mean just going into town.

84
00:05:49,448 --> 00:05:52,815
It means Macon and
Atlanta and still further.

85
00:05:52,985 --> 00:05:58,082
I've been to Atlanta, you know
that. When I was no older than you.

86
00:05:58,257 --> 00:06:03,251
I told you how them folks laughed
at me and called me smart names.

87
00:06:03,429 --> 00:06:04,987
You don't want that, boy.

88
00:06:05,531 --> 00:06:09,433
-Pa, now ain't the same as it was then.
-Dogged if it ain't.

89
00:06:09,602 --> 00:06:14,062
But they want me. They even sent a
fella to come and fetch me, didn't they?

90
00:06:14,240 --> 00:06:15,707
And that ain't all.

91
00:06:15,875 --> 00:06:19,709
Last spring, I seen a sign on
the sidewalk down there in town.

92
00:06:19,879 --> 00:06:23,508
This great big old
picture of Uncle Sam.

93
00:06:23,683 --> 00:06:27,084
"And Uncle Sam wants
you," he's a-saying.

94
00:06:27,420 --> 00:06:31,982
Just like this fellow here, Pa, pointing
his finger right straight in my face.

95
00:06:32,491 --> 00:06:35,688
Don't you think a soldier fella
come up to me right then and there...

96
00:06:35,861 --> 00:06:39,092
...inviting me to come
along with all the other fellas?

97
00:06:39,865 --> 00:06:42,698
I told him how you
was ailing then...

98
00:06:42,868 --> 00:06:46,429
...and would he
kindly wait a while.

99
00:06:48,941 --> 00:06:51,466
You've been tearing up
them letters, ain't you, Pa?

100
00:06:54,547 --> 00:06:57,107
And you ain't ailing no more.

101
00:07:09,562 --> 00:07:14,158
-Hey, are you coming or do I have to--
-I'm just fixing to get me my shoes.

102
00:07:16,035 --> 00:07:18,128
You've got to know this:

103
00:07:18,304 --> 00:07:20,101
He's a good boy.

104
00:07:20,272 --> 00:07:22,832
It's my blame he didn't
come when he should've.

105
00:07:23,009 --> 00:07:25,477
I don't care who or why,
mister. We got him now.

106
00:07:25,645 --> 00:07:29,046
Remember, Pa? I got these
here for Aunt Tuzie's funeral.

107
00:07:29,215 --> 00:07:32,776
Ain't it nice I'm finally getting
a chance to wear them again?

108
00:07:34,186 --> 00:07:36,177
Appears they liked
to have shrunk a little.

109
00:07:36,355 --> 00:07:37,879
They'll put shoes
on you in Army.

110
00:07:38,057 --> 00:07:40,252
And ain't gonna wait
for you to put them on.

111
00:07:40,426 --> 00:07:45,125
Listen, draft man, you tell them
folks to be nice to my boy, you hear?

112
00:07:45,297 --> 00:07:47,697
-lf they ain't, I'll--
-I'm ready.

113
00:07:56,676 --> 00:07:59,668
Say goodbye to Blue for me
when he wakes up, will you?

114
00:07:59,845 --> 00:08:01,210
I will.

115
00:08:01,580 --> 00:08:06,313
-Write to me regular, you hear?
-Sure, Pa.

116
00:08:08,254 --> 00:08:09,778
Print big.

117
00:08:10,356 --> 00:08:12,119
I will.

118
00:08:13,859 --> 00:08:16,953
Remember, draft
man, what I said.

119
00:08:17,129 --> 00:08:20,064
-lf they ain't good to my boy....
-Yeah, I'll remember.

120
00:08:20,232 --> 00:08:22,166
Come on, boy, we gotta go.

121
00:08:22,334 --> 00:08:25,360
-Bye, Pa.
-Bye, Will.

